        "type": "method",
        "name": "orthogonal",
        "return_type": {
          "qualified_name": null,
          "simple_name": "Vector3D",
          "is_array": false,
          "array_dimensions": 0
        },
        "parameters": [],
        "javadoc": "/**\n * Get a vector orthogonal to the instance.\n * <p>There are an infinite number of normalized vectors orthogonal\n * to the instance. This method picks up one of them almost\n * arbitrarily. It is useful when one needs to compute a reference\n * frame with one of the axes in a predefined direction. The\n * following example shows how to build a frame having the k axis\n * aligned with the known vector u :\n * <pre><code>\n *   Vector3D k = u.normalize();\n *   Vector3D i = k.orthogonal();\n *   Vector3D j = Vector3D.crossProduct(k, i);\n * </code></pre></p>\n * @return a new normalized vector orthogonal to the instance\n * @exception MathArithmeticException if the norm of the instance is null\n */\n",
        "tags": [
          {
            "tag": "return",
            "name": null,
            "content": "new normalized vector orthogonal to the instance",
            "assertion": "assert methodResultID != null && !methodResultID.equals(receiverObjectID);",
            "description": "a new normalized vector orthogonal to the instance"
          },
          {
            "tag": "throws",
            "name": "MathArithmeticException",
            "content": "if the norm of the instance is null",
            "assertion": "",
            "description": "if the norm of the instance is null"
          }
        ],
        "code": "/**\n * Get a vector orthogonal to the instance.\n * <p>There are an infinite number of normalized vectors orthogonal\n * to the instance. This method picks up one of them almost\n * arbitrarily. It is useful when one needs to compute a reference\n * frame with one of the axes in a predefined direction. The\n * following example shows how to build a frame having the k axis\n * aligned with the known vector u :\n * <pre><code>\n *   Vector3D k = u.normalize();\n *   Vector3D i = k.orthogonal();\n *   Vector3D j = Vector3D.crossProduct(k, i);\n * </code></pre></p>\n * @return a new normalized vector orthogonal to the instance\n * @exception MathArithmeticException if the norm of the instance is null\n */\npublic Vector3D orthogonal() throws MathArithmeticException {\n    double threshold = 0.6 * getNorm();\n    if (threshold == 0) {\n        throw new MathArithmeticException(LocalizedFormats.ZERO_NORM);\n    }\n    if (FastMath.abs(x) <= threshold) {\n        double inverse = 1 / FastMath.sqrt(y * y + z * z);\n        return new Vector3D(0, inverse * z, -inverse * y);\n    } else if (FastMath.abs(y) <= threshold) {\n        double inverse = 1 / FastMath.sqrt(x * x + z * z);\n        return new Vector3D(-inverse * z, 0, inverse * x);\n    }\n    double inverse = 1 / FastMath.sqrt(x * x + y * y);\n    return new Vector3D(inverse * y, -inverse * x, 0);\n}"
      },
